body:
### Component

Forge

### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?

- [ ] Foundry
- [ ] Foundryup

### What version of Foundry are you on?

forge 0.2.0 (91f69dd 2023-05-01T19:02:48.262468700Z)

### What command(s) is the bug in?

forge test

### Operating System

Windows

### Describe the bug

I'm using WSL 1 in Windows.

```solidity
function testAssertError(uint256 i) public {
        uint decimals = 8;
        uint256 MAX_UINT256 = 2 ** 256 - 1;
        vm.assume(i <= MAX_UINT256 / 10 ** (18 + decimals) + 1);
        assertLe(i, MAX_UINT256 / 10 ** (18 + decimals));
}
```

Why this test doesn't fails?

If I remove the `vm.assume` line then test fails on `1157920892373161954235709850086879078532699846656406` which is equals to `MAX_UINT256 / 10 ** (18 + decimals) + 1`. So even if `vm.assume` allows the value `1157920892373161954235709850086879078532699846656406`, it skips this value but if `vm.assume` line is removed then it includes this value.

**EDIT**

Using bound fixes the issue:

```solidity
function testAssertError(uint256 i) public {
        uint decimals = 8;
        uint256 MAX_UINT256 = 2 ** 256 - 1;
        i = bound(i, 0, MAX_UINT256 / 10 ** (18 + decimals) + 1);
        assertLe(i, MAX_UINT256 / 10 ** (18 + decimals));
}
```

But still, why does vm.assume skips the value?
